WEBVTT

00:08.940 --> 00:12.880
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.540 --> 00:33.900
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.580 --> 00:38.220
And here are your hosts.

00:42.540 --> 00:43.640
This is Daryl Lane.

00:43.900 --> 00:44.560
And David Carson.

00:44.980 --> 00:48.000
Few individuals have had the impact on science fiction that Damon Knight has.

00:48.600 --> 00:52.040
He's written quality short stories and novels, of course, since his first published work

00:52.040 --> 00:53.700
over 40 years ago in 1941.

00:54.280 --> 00:55.960
But he's done so much else for the field.

00:56.280 --> 00:59.600
He's recognized as the first and perhaps still the best critic of science fiction.

01:00.100 --> 01:03.900
He founded the Science Fiction Writers of America, and he initiated the Milford Science

01:03.900 --> 01:06.200
Fiction Writers Conference for authors of science fiction.

01:06.740 --> 01:10.720
He's also one of the premier editors in science fiction, having constructed enough anthologies

01:10.720 --> 01:11.540
to fill a library.

01:11.980 --> 01:14.960
We spoke with Knight recently and asked him how he got a start in science fiction.

01:15.420 --> 01:18.400
I thought that might come up, and I was rooting about it really yesterday.

01:21.600 --> 01:27.080
Actually, I was thinking, what if you asked me what do I attribute my gigantic success

01:27.080 --> 01:28.540
that would have to say mostly luck?

01:29.480 --> 01:35.660
I can trace my career back through a series of just astounding coincidences, really unlikely

01:35.660 --> 01:38.740
things, all the way back to Hulu Gernsback.

01:39.700 --> 01:43.740
And I can demonstrate that at each of these points, if something rather unlikely had not

01:43.740 --> 01:45.320
happened, I wouldn't be doing what I'm doing.

01:46.560 --> 01:50.820
For instance, if Hulu Gernsback had not come to this country from Luxembourg when he was

01:50.820 --> 01:59.260
14 and started a magazine called Amazing Stories in 1926, you'll see as I go on that

01:59.260 --> 02:00.420
none of the other things could have happened.

02:00.620 --> 02:06.160
So here I am, a 13-year-old kid in a literary and reading science fiction magazine, really

02:06.160 --> 02:07.860
turned on the item.

02:08.060 --> 02:14.660
And through the back pages of one of these magazines, Super Science Stories, then edited

02:14.660 --> 02:21.660
by Frederick Polk, I found out about fanzines and wrote away for a few, and this boy got

02:21.660 --> 02:23.200
into correspondence with the Futurians.

02:24.240 --> 02:27.520
The Futurians were a group of young science fiction fans who later became some of the

02:27.520 --> 02:29.120
major writers and editors in the field.

02:29.520 --> 02:34.060
At the time, they included Frederick Polk, Donal A. Walheim, Cyril Cornbluth, and Robert

02:34.060 --> 02:34.940
W. Lowndes.

02:35.380 --> 02:40.100
I was trying to write some stories, and I sent a couple to Lowndes who was then acting

02:40.100 --> 02:41.740
as a thorough half-assed literary agent.

02:43.800 --> 02:51.280
And all these things added up together until Donal A. Walheim got an offer from a publisher

02:51.280 --> 02:53.040
who edited a new science fiction magazine.

02:53.320 --> 02:54.980
He had no budget for whatever, for stories.

02:56.160 --> 02:57.700
And he knew about me from Lowndes.

02:57.820 --> 03:02.340
Lowndes wrote to me saying, will you donate the story to the first issue of Super Science

03:02.340 --> 03:02.940
Stories?

03:04.300 --> 03:07.040
And of course I said yes, I would have paid for the privilege.

03:08.380 --> 03:14.820
And as a consequence of that, the Futurians invited me to come and be a Futurian, live

03:14.820 --> 03:17.180
one of their communal dwellings in New York when I was 18.

03:18.660 --> 03:20.060
Terribly unlikely things.

03:20.200 --> 03:22.780
Just a series of them, even as far as I've gone.

03:24.160 --> 03:28.820
And I was there a couple years doing a little illustration from magazines and trying to write,

03:29.560 --> 03:31.080
and not particularly very much.

03:32.720 --> 03:41.420
And then in 1943, again, this Fred Poole got me a job at popular publications where he was working.

03:41.660 --> 03:45.680
I needed an assistant editor, and he knew I would work cheap.

03:46.020 --> 03:48.200
So he got me an interview, and I got the job.

03:48.640 --> 03:53.340
I spent about a year there, and I'm perfectly convinced now, looking back, that it was that

03:53.340 --> 03:57.220
training at popular publications that enabled me to write fiction professionally.

03:58.340 --> 04:01.960
It was a training that you couldn't get in any school, and I doubt if you could get it now.

04:02.740 --> 04:07.100
But it just kind of soaked in, because I was reading this watch pile, the Unpoliced

04:07.100 --> 04:12.060
Good Banscript, and it became perfectly obvious after a while what the difference was between

04:12.060 --> 04:14.340
the stuff we were rejecting and the stuff we were printing.

04:15.660 --> 04:17.560
So when I quit that job, I started writing.

04:26.680 --> 04:30.700
Night began publishing science fiction stories, many of which have become classics today,

04:31.120 --> 04:35.280
but he also continued his editing and considers such work as the ideal training ground for young

04:35.280 --> 04:36.160
science fiction writers.

04:54.920 --> 04:56.560
More with Damon Knight next time.

05:40.560 --> 05:47.540
Thanks for watching.

