06:33.660 --> 06:37.560
Damon Knight's apprenticeship to science fiction came as a member of the Futurians, a group

06:37.560 --> 06:41.640
of fans in the 1930s who later became some of the principal editors and writers in the field.

06:41.640 --> 06:45.400
Knight has written a book about the Futurians, published in 1977.

06:46.140 --> 06:47.220
He reminisces about the group.

06:47.960 --> 06:55.860
Well, the Futurians were a very informal organization of science fiction fans who were trying to become

06:55.860 --> 07:01.520
professionals, and in some cases had had little bits of success here and there in the published

07:01.520 --> 07:01.900
stories.

07:03.140 --> 07:07.820
And I told you that Walheim was editing a magazine before him, who had become an editor.

07:08.380 --> 07:11.000
And after him, Lowndes also became an editor.

07:12.100 --> 07:14.500
And they were writing and publishing a little bit, not much.

07:15.360 --> 07:20.200
And to save money because they were all very poor, they lived in a county old apartment.

07:22.220 --> 07:27.120
At that time in New York in the late 30s and early 40s, there were lots of apartments from

07:27.120 --> 07:27.960
where they were very cheap.

07:29.320 --> 07:30.400
I forget now.

07:30.500 --> 07:35.800
I think the rental might have been about $30 bucks for a four bedroom railroad flat.

07:36.440 --> 07:38.640
If you had four people living there, it was quite cheap.

07:40.300 --> 07:42.080
And we divided up the household duties.

07:42.240 --> 07:45.000
Round with the cooking and I did the fish washing, which I hated.

07:47.760 --> 07:48.900
We were dirt poor.

07:49.040 --> 07:50.500
We really didn't have any money at all.

07:51.440 --> 07:57.520
We rolled our own cigarettes and we bought the cheapest wine we could find, which was

07:57.520 --> 07:59.140
something like 85 cents a gallon.

08:02.540 --> 08:08.140
Our major entertainment was walking down from the 102nd Street or 103rd, if I was

08:08.140 --> 08:12.580
bound, to Times Square and looking at the bright lights and having a cup of coffee in

08:12.580 --> 08:14.520
the cafeteria and then walking home.

08:36.880 --> 08:41.240
Before Knight became recognized as an author of science fiction, he worked on fanzines,

08:41.440 --> 08:43.000
as an editor, and as a book reviewer.

08:43.360 --> 08:46.880
Out of his experiences as a book reviewer, Knight developed some critical principles that he

08:46.880 --> 08:47.920
applied to science fiction.

08:48.340 --> 08:51.880
And he actually became the first and probably still the best critic of the field.

08:52.320 --> 08:56.220
Knight talks about that period of his development in the 1940s when he began writing criticism.

08:57.200 --> 09:01.100
I was trying to write fiction at that time and not succeeding.

09:01.320 --> 09:02.160
I couldn't finish the story.

09:02.280 --> 09:04.520
I didn't have any idea how you got to the end of the story.

09:06.760 --> 09:12.600
But I was extremely critical and starting like any other, right, 17 or 18 year old fan.

09:15.560 --> 09:19.420
The first stuff I did for fanzines was not critical in the usual sense.

09:19.660 --> 09:22.240
I mean, it wasn't book reviews or what kind of thing.

09:22.240 --> 09:24.080
But it was parody mostly.

09:25.160 --> 09:32.700
The things that I thought were really outstandingly dumb in the magazine, funny enough to parody.

09:33.600 --> 09:34.820
I did a lot of that.

09:36.200 --> 09:42.860
But when I say a lot, I lie because I only published two issues of my fanzine and did very little

09:42.860 --> 09:43.960
for other magazines.

09:43.960 --> 09:50.820
It was much later, about 1945, I think, that I did a long critical essay about that.

09:50.940 --> 09:53.920
Those were one of Larry Shaw's amateur magazines.

09:54.820 --> 09:59.320
That was really the first critical work in the usual sense, correct?

10:00.620 --> 10:05.160
Knight's criticism in book reviews were published in 1967 as a book entitled In Search of Wonder,

10:05.420 --> 10:07.480
a landmark since it was the first book of its kind.

10:07.940 --> 10:11.980
What Knight basically tried to do in his criticism was raise science fiction writing to a higher level,

10:11.980 --> 10:15.800
to establish standards for it that would make it the equal of mainstream literature and quality.

