12:23.520 --> 12:27.860
Damon Knight's influence on science fiction is indisputable, and it's made itself felt in many different ways.

12:28.640 --> 12:32.920
Knight was the originator of the science fiction writers of America, for example, back in 1965.

12:33.540 --> 12:35.280
We asked him how the organization came about.

12:36.460 --> 12:38.560
About ten years earlier, it must have been.

12:39.880 --> 12:44.900
There was an effort to form a guild of science fiction writers, and I went to one or two of their meetings,

12:46.020 --> 12:51.920
and it was pitiful because they used the program in their procedure, and they had 50 people all arguing.

12:52.860 --> 12:59.700
And they finally hammered out a sort of set of bylaws and elected officers, and then nothing happened.

13:00.060 --> 13:01.720
Officers all went home and just died.

13:02.820 --> 13:06.900
And I realized at that time that there was a very easy way to do it.

13:06.960 --> 13:11.120
You didn't have to have the big meetings, and you didn't have to have all that apparatus.

13:11.380 --> 13:16.080
One person could do it, but I didn't think I was conspicuous about it at that time.

13:16.180 --> 13:17.940
I didn't think anybody knew who I was.

13:19.600 --> 13:29.000
Later on, I was becoming more visible, and I realized that I probably could do it.

13:29.000 --> 13:41.920
The precipitating event was by receiving in the same week three requests for anthology reprints for flat C's, which I thought was unfair to the author.

13:42.680 --> 13:45.460
So I wrote a flyer, it's a one-page thing.

13:46.900 --> 13:52.480
Advising authors not to sign agreements for flat C anthology reprints and things.

13:52.600 --> 13:57.280
You'd like more information of this kind, send in your three bucks, and become a charter member of SFWA.

13:59.000 --> 14:07.220
I had about 78, I declared them the charter members, and wrote a set of bylaws and sent that around, and we were more of a business.

14:08.680 --> 14:18.200
The science fiction writers of America has helped authors in various ways, for example by helping them get better contracts from publishers by fighting legal battles and providing encouragement and professional recognition.

14:18.660 --> 14:24.360
Another thing Knight was responsible for was to act as the co-founder of the Milford Science Fiction Writers Conference in 1956.

14:24.820 --> 14:29.140
The Milford Conference was conceived by Knight and Judith Merrill as an aid to science fiction writers.

14:29.640 --> 14:34.560
It provided them with an opportunity to have their work read and criticized by other professional science fiction writers.

14:34.940 --> 14:37.060
Knight talks about how the Milford Conference began.

14:37.600 --> 14:48.760
Well, this was in the mid-50s, and for some reason, Judy Merrill and I got talking about the idea of having a writer's conference in Milford, Pennsylvania, which is a very small town in the Poconos.

14:51.000 --> 14:54.660
It was sort of the way you might talk about building a building and basement.

14:56.440 --> 15:07.000
And nothing was done about this until Judy and I went through the World Con in Detroit at the Kivon, and the courage that we were much more better than we realized.

15:08.440 --> 15:13.540
Well, that energized us, and we thought that, honestly, if we invited people to the Milford base, we'd actually come.

15:14.880 --> 15:21.900
And we sent out invitations. We got Jim Wisch to join the Mast Ed, funded more respectability.

15:23.540 --> 15:32.920
And this was the year in which the World Con was falling here. The World Con was in New York, so it was easier for people to get out there directly afterwards.

15:33.640 --> 15:38.060
And we got 40 people. Just amazing. It was quite intense.

15:39.600 --> 15:50.220
We had evening discussions that went on for several hours, and people raising their hands to do the next to speak. Quite exciting.

16:01.160 --> 16:07.940
A regular feature of the conference was the workshop, in which authors would submit manuscripts and have them criticized by other members of the conference.

16:08.400 --> 16:13.040
Damon Knight and his wife Kate Wellhelm now conduct the Clarion Workshop in science fiction and fantasy.

16:13.040 --> 16:20.580
The Clarion Workshop is based on the same idea as the Milford Workshop, though attending writers are beginners for the most part, and Knight and Wellhelm are the teachers.

16:20.980 --> 16:27.700
Professional writers of science fiction and beginning writers too, who have hopes of becoming established professionals, have a great deal to thank Damon Knight for.

