18:16.620 --> 18:21.920
Damon Knight's best science fiction has a real cutting edge to it, some sort of satire, irony, or social criticism.

18:23.000 --> 18:29.240
A good example is a second novel published in 1959 as The People-Maker, but reissued under Knight's preferred title, A for Anything.

18:29.240 --> 18:34.900
The story focuses on the question of how society would change if a matter duplicator were suddenly given to mankind.

18:35.180 --> 18:41.440
The duplicator, called the gizmo, can copy anything, a tool, a building, a weapon, a vehicle, even a human being.

18:42.040 --> 18:47.500
Optimists may think society would be enormously benefited from such a device, but that's not the way it turns out in Knight's novel.

18:47.900 --> 18:48.500
Quite the reverse.

18:48.920 --> 18:54.660
The social structure becomes futile, with a few rich and powerful families controlling everything through the power of the gizmo.

18:54.660 --> 18:59.680
And slavery is a fact of life too. The majority of the people are poor and exploited by the powerful.

19:00.340 --> 19:07.540
For most of the novel, it seems the protagonist, the son of a rich and powerful gizmo owner, will aid in a slave revolt which will overthrow the oppressive society.

19:08.020 --> 19:13.960
But on the final page of the novel, he shoots the wise old slave who has been leading the revolt and chooses to remain a rich tyrant.

19:14.280 --> 19:19.100
It's got to be one of the most depressing endings a science fiction novel ever had. We asked Knight why he produced it.

19:20.040 --> 19:24.880
Well, what you're talking about, the ending that you expected is the cliche ending.

19:26.040 --> 19:29.360
Romantic and sentimental. I wanted to do a realistic ending.

19:30.320 --> 19:36.700
I thought that a happy ending to that, you know, conventional quote, happy ending to that novel would have been wrong.

19:38.220 --> 19:41.620
And this was one of the things that interested me in writing the novel in the first place.

19:42.100 --> 19:44.780
You know, anything I've done is a second cover of this plastic.

19:44.780 --> 19:56.880
I was trying to do science fiction realistically. I thought that was part of the new way that was called at then, but the way of realism, the cane and the fishing.

19:58.040 --> 20:02.460
And I was awfully acquired, still I am, of the romantic cliches of science fiction.

20:03.440 --> 20:08.700
We asked Knight why such a marvelous device as the gizmo would result in a tyrannical slave-oriented society.

20:08.700 --> 20:25.120
Well, I thought it was logical. I was counter punching in that novel against some other treatments of the same device, the same gadget that had been published before, which I thought were compouts.

20:25.900 --> 20:38.100
For instance, George O. Snedt wrote one in which the matter that the applicator was embedded and, of course, chaos ensued, and he rescued the world by inventing a kind of currency that couldn't be duplicated.

20:39.400 --> 20:42.100
And that was one too many rabbits out of a hat, I thought.

20:43.600 --> 20:46.480
So, again, I just wanted to do it realistically.

20:46.480 --> 21:00.400
It seemed to me that if I had made a good case that the fact that slavery would be the result, I admit that it was an imaginative projection.

21:00.740 --> 21:05.540
I don't necessarily defend the idea that that's what would happen in practice.

21:06.780 --> 21:13.380
And another writer, several years later, wrote a story in response to that one, which really delighted me.

21:13.500 --> 21:27.920
I like this dialogue and the second time, which in which he showed that a good marketer, a good business man could get along personally well and make money, even if there was a matter of duplicators.

21:28.780 --> 21:29.400
Marvelous story.

